which he did not as yet think proper to lay
a&s;ide; for, he was not more ambitious in the
plan, than indefatigable in the pro&s;ecution of it.
He knew it would be impo&s;&s;ible to execute his
<PB N="38" REF="47">
aims upon the count's daughter, under the eye
of Tere&s;a, who&s;e natural di&s;cernment would be
whetted with jealou&s;y, and who would watch
his conduct, and thwart his progre&s;s with all the
