<P>He &s;eldom or never erred in his ob&s;ervations
on the human heart. Tere&s;a, in&s;tead of di&s;|approving,
reli&s;hed the plan in general, with de|mon&s;trations
of &s;ingular &s;atisfaction: &s;he, at once
conceived all the advantageous con&s;equences of
&s;uch a &s;cheme, and perceived in it, only one
flaw, which, however, &s;he did not think incurable.
This defect was no other than a &s;ufficient bond
of union, by which they might be effectually
